{"title_page": "Dieter Appelt", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Dieter Appelt\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = <!-- use the image's pagename; do not include the \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and do not use brackets-->\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1935|03|03}} \n| birth_place      = [[Niemegk]], [[Brandenburg]], Germany\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality      = [[Germany|German]]\n| residence        = [[Berlin]]\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = Photography, Painting and Sculpture\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = \n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = \n| module           = \n}}\n'''Dieter Appelt''' (born [[Niemegk]], 3 March 1935) is a German photographer, painter, sculptor and video artist.\n\nHe studied music from 1954 to 1958 in the Mendelssohn Bartholdy Akademie in [[Leipzig]]. There, he discovers and develops a strong interest for [[Impressionism]], [[Fauvism]], and [[Russian constructivism]]. In 1959, he leaves [[East Germany]] and settles in [[West Berlin]] to study in the music school of Berlin until 1964. That same year, he decides to study fine art and he takes his first steps in [[painting]], [[photography]], [[etching]], and [[sculpture]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/dieter-appelt/biography|title=Dieter Appelt Biography \u2013 Dieter Appelt on artnet|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref> In the 1970s, he makes his appearance on the public stage, with his first exhibition at the [[Deutsche Oper Berlin]] in 1974. In 1976 he focuses on visual arts and his career as an artist takes off. Appelt is also known for his works on the mechanics and techniques of photography that he made in the 1980s. In 1990 and 1999, he took part in the [[Venice Biennale]]. During this decade, Dieter Appelt exhibited in several major capitals of the world including: [[Tokyo]], [[New York City|New-York]], [[Berlin]], [[Moscow]], [[Budapest]], [[Montreal]], and [[Edinburgh]]. He lives and works in Berlin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.galeriethomasschulte.de/artist/dieter-appelt/#|title=Dieter Appelt \u2013 Galerie Thomas Schulte|website=www.galeriethomasschulte.de|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web\n |url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/events/2692/dieter-appelt-the-catastrophe-of-things\n |title=Dieter Appelt: The Catastrophe of Things (17 April to 4 August 1996), CCA, Montr\u00e9al, Octagonal \n |publisher=[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] \n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Appelt, Dieter}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century German painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century German painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:21st-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:German photographers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Academy of the Arts, Berlin]]\n\n\n{{germany-artist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Dieter Appelt\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = <!-- use the image's pagename; do not include the \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and do not use brackets-->\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1935|03|03}} \n| birth_place      = [[Niemegk]], [[Brandenburg]], Germany\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality      = [[Germany|German]]\n| residence        = [[Berlin]]\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = Photography, Painting and Sculpture\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = \n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = \n| module           = \n}}\n'''Dieter Appelt''' (born [[Niemegk]], 3 March 1935) is a German photographer, painter, sculptor and video artist.\n\nHe studied music from 1954 to 1958 in the Mendelssohn Bartholdy Akademie in [[Leipzig]]. There, he discovers and develops a strong interest for [[Impressionism]], [[Fauvism]], and [[Russian constructivism]]. In 1959, he leaves [[East Germany]] and settles in [[West Berlin]] to study in the music school of Berlin until 1964. That same year, he decides to study fine art and he takes his first steps in [[painting]], [[photography]], [[etching]], and [[sculpture]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/dieter-appelt/biography|title=Dieter Appelt Biography \u2013 Dieter Appelt on artnet|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref> In the 1970s, he makes his appearance on the public stage, with his first exhibition at the [[Deutsche Oper Berlin]] in 1974. In 1976 he focuses on visual arts and his career as an artist takes off. Appelt is also known for his works on the mechanics and techniques of photography that he made in the 1980s. In 1990 and 1999, he took part in the [[Venice Biennale]]. During this decade, Dieter Appelt exhibited in several major capitals of the world including: [[Tokyo]], [[New York City|New-York]], [[Berlin]], [[Moscow]], [[Budapest]], [[Montreal]], and [[Edinburgh]]. He lives and works in Berlin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.galeriethomasschulte.de/artist/dieter-appelt/#|title=Dieter Appelt \u2013 Galerie Thomas Schulte|website=www.galeriethomasschulte.de|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web\n |accessdate=2008-08-16 \n |url=http://www.cca.qc.ca/pages/Niveau3.asp?page=dieter&lang=eng \n |title=Dieter Appelt: The Catastrophe of Things (17 April to 4 August 1996), CCA, Montr\u00e9al, Octagonal \n |publisher=Canadian Centre for Architecture \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808005926/http://cca.qc.ca/pages/Niveau3.asp?page=dieter&lang=eng \n |archivedate=2007-08-08 \n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Appelt, Dieter}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century German painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century German painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:21st-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:German photographers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Academy of the Arts, Berlin]]\n\n\n{{germany-artist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sadebag", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:corrected link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dieter_Appelt"}
